    "chunk_id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_1999_Solutions_1999s_page_001_11",
    "text": "Second solution: We proceed by induction on the degree of p, with base case where p has degree 0. As in the first solution, we may reduce to a smaller degree in case p has any real roots, so assume it has none. Then p(x) > 0 for all real x, and since p(x) → oo for x → 100, p has a minimum value c. Now p(x) - c has real roots, so as above, we deduce that p(x) - c is a sum of squares. Now add one more square, namely (Vc)?, to get p(x) as a sum of squares.",
